Bring a #large pot{} of @salted water{} to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Halve @grape tomatoes{4%ounce}.

Drop @cream cheese{2%tablespoon} packets in a #glass{} of warm water to soften.

Once water is boiling, add @spaghetti{6%ounce} to #pot{}. Cook, stirring occasionally,
until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}. Reserve ½ cup pasta cooking water (1 cup for 4 servings),
then drain.

In a #medium bowl{}, combine cream cheese, @ricotta cheese{4%ounce}, half the
@Parmesan cheese{6%tablespoon}, and a drizzle of @olive oil{1%teaspoon} (large drizzle
for 4 servings).

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%teaspoon} in #pot{} used for pasta over medium-high
heat. Add tomatoes and cook, stirring occasionally, until softened and lightly browned,
~{2-3%minutes}. Add @Tuscan Heat Spice{1%tablespoon} and cook, stirring, until fragrant,
~{20-30%seconds} more.

Gradually stir in cheese mixture and ¼ cup reserved pasta cooking water (½ cup for 4
servings) and cook until creamy and thoroughly combined, ~{1-2%minutes}.
> TIP: If sauce seems too thick, add more splashes of reserved pasta cooking water 1 TBSP at a time.
Season with @salt{} to taste. Remove from heat.

Stir @butter{1%tablespoon} (2 TBSP for 4 servings) and a big pinch of @pepper{} into
pot with sauce. Return pot to stovetop over medium heat. Add drained spaghetti and
@spinach{2.5%ounce} and cook, stirring, until spinach is slightly wilted and pasta is
coated, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Divide pasta between #shallow bowls{}. Top with remaining Parmesan and serve.